":"1270","1170":"1170","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","Abt 1195":"about 1195","1226":"1226","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","       1228":"1228","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1299":"1299","Church Lawton, Cheshire, England":"Church Lawton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Haydock,Lancashire,England":"Haydock, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lauton, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Haydock, Warrington, Lancashire, England, UK":"Haydock, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lauton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Leighton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Leighton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Leighton or Layton. Most, as for example those in Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Lancashire, and Shropshire, are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, but Layton in Durham derives from Old English <i>ge-lād</i> ‘road’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The English pronunciation of <i>Leighton</i> is usually /lɛ:tən/ or /leitən/ (also spelled   Layton   and   Leaton  ), but it can also be heard as /laitən/ or as /li:tən/ (also spelled   Leaton  ), and occasionally as /lɛtən/ (spelled   Letton  )."]},{"name":"Leyton","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Juan Carlos, Alonso, Amalia, Ana, Carlos, Erasmo, Fernando, Jorge, Jose Carlos, Mauricio.","English: variant of   Layton  .","Spanish: altered form of Galician <b>Leitón</b>, a nickname meaning ‘suckling pig’."]}]},{"name":"Cecelia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":20,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":29,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":64,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https